\begin{slide}{Network Topology}
 For the sake of this course, we will focus on switched (or bridged) networksdesigned to the "Star" topology.
 99\% of networks you will encounter are Star-topology networks, and this course is intended to be an overview of
 cyber defense principles to apply in design and analysis of networks.
\end{slide}

\begin{slide}{Device Terminology}
 Key device terms to be used in this course
 \begin{description}
  \item[Bridge] Interconnects multiple devices, enabling them to communicate directly with one another on a common network.
  \item[Router] "A router is used to route data packets between two networks."\cite{CompTech:NetGuide:NetDevs}
  \item[Firewall] "Firewalls are mainly used as a means to protect an organization's internal network from those on the outside (internet)." "Firewalls are also used to limit the access of individuals on the internal network to services on the internet along with keeping track of what is done through the firewall."\cite{CompTech:NetGuide:Firewalls}
 \end{description}
\end{slide}

\begin{slide}{Device Terminology (cont.)}
 Key device terms to be used in this course
 \begin{description}
  \item[Server] A device installed on the network which is providing resources to users with access to that network
  \item[Gateway] "A gateway can translate information between different network data formats or network architectures"\cite{CompTech:NetGuide:NetDevs}
  \item[Endpoint] Used to describe a computer, typically a PC, on the network which is regularly connecting a user to the network, and possibly the Internet.
 \end{description}
\end{slide}

